anizing for global and local social justice, highlighting their important contributions to contemporary social movements and social theory.Rebel Girls explores how teenage girls construct activist identities, rejecting and redefining girlhood and claiming political authority for youth in the process. Taft examines the girl activists’ social movement strategies and collective political practices, detailing their shared commitments to process-based political education, participatory democracy, and hopeful enthusiasm. Ultimately, Rebel Girls has substantial implications for social movements and youth organizations, arguing that adult social movements could learn a great deal from girl activists and making clear the importance of increased collaboration between young people and adults.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aSocial actionzAmerica. 0aTeenage girlsxPolitical activityzAmerica. 0aYouthxPolitical activityzAmerica. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aRebel.  aactivist.  aauthority.  aclaiming.  aconstruct.  aexplores.  agirlhood.  agirls.  aidentities.  apolitical.  aprocess.  aredefining.  arejecting.  ateenage.  ayouth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081478324540uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814784204.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814784204423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814784204/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK